21","1151":"1151","1194":"1194","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1117–":"1117–Overleden","1117–Male":"1117–Overleden","1121–Female":"1121–Overleden","1147–1194":"1147–1194","1149–Male":"1149–Overleden","1151–Female":"1151–Overleden","1091–Male":"1091–Overleden","1091":"1091","1117":"1117","1149":"1149","1215":"1215","1147":"1147","1224":"1224","1121":"1121","1151":"1151","1194":"1194","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1117–":"1117–Deceased","1117–Male":"1117–Deceased","1121–Female":"1121–Deceased","1147–1194":"1147–1194","1149–Male":"1149–Deceased","1151–Female":"1151–Deceased","1091–Male":"1091–Deceased","1091":"1091","1117":"1117","1149":"1149","1215":"1215","1147":"1147","1224":"1224","1121":"1121","1151":"1151","1194":"1194","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leighton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Leighton or Layton. Most, as for example those in Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Lancashire, and Shropshire, are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, but Layton in Durham derives from Old English <i>ge-lād</i> ‘road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English pronunciation of <i>Leighton</i> is usually /lɛ:tən/ or /leitən/ (also spelled   Layton   and   Leaton  ), but it can also be heard as /laitən/ or as /li:tən/ (also spelled   Leaton  ), and occasionally as /lɛtən/ (spelled   Letton  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Layton","meanings":["English: variant of   Leighton  ."]},{"name":"Slayton","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Leighton   (compare   Layton  ) with the addition of initial <i>S-</i>. Alternatively, perhaps a variant of   Sladen   or of <b>Sleightholme</b>, principally a habitational name from Sleightholme Dale in Kirkbymoorside, but perhaps occasionally from Sleightholme in Bowes or the lost Sleightholme in Lythe. The placenames derive from Old Norse <i>sléttr</i> ‘smooth, level’ + <i>holmr</i> ‘small island, water meadow’. This surname is now very rare in Britain. Compare   Slaydon  ."]},{"name":"Leaton","meanings":["English: variant of   Leighton  ."]},{"name":"Laughton","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Laughton en le Morthen in Yorkshire, Laughton in Leicestershire or any of the two places called Laughton in Lincolnshire (one near Gainsborough and another near Folkingham). The places are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure’, meaning ‘village or farm where leeks are grown’. It may sometimes have alternated with   Leighton  , which is mostly from placenames with the same etymology.","variant of   Lawton  ."]},{"name":"Letton","meanings":["English: habitational name, most probably from Letton in Norfolk or Latton in Essex. It could also be a variant of   Leighton   or   Laughton  . Most of the places so named have the same etymology as Letton and Latton, i.e. ‘farm where leeks are grown’ (Old English <i>lēac-tūn</i>). Another possibility is that it is a variant of   Latten  ."]}]},{"name":"Titus","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an old Roman given name, of unknown ultimate origin. It was borne by a companion of  St Paul  who became the first bishop of Crete, and also by the Roman emperor who destroyed Jerusalem in   ad  70 . It is remembered in England as the name of the clergyman and anti-Catholic conspirator  Titus Oates  (  1649–1705 ), who fabricated the so-called  Popish Plot  (  1678 ) to kill  Charles II  and his Protestant supporters. The name has never been very common in the English-speaking world, but is recorded regularly in some families from the 17th century onwards."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":98,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":107,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Titus de Leighton was born in 1117, in Leighton, Shropshire, England as the son of Cuthbert De LEIGHTON . He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Leticia le Brun."},"et":{"1117–":"1117–Surnud","1117–Male":"1117–Surnud","1121–Female":"1121–Surnud","1147–1194":"1147–1194","1149–Male":"1149–Surnud","1151–Female":"1151–Surnud","1091–Male":"1091–Surnud","1091":"1091","1117":"1117","1149":"1149","1215":"1215","1147":"1147","1224":"1224","1121":"1121","1151":"1151","1194":"1194","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1117–":"1117–Kuollut","1117–Male":"1117–Kuollut","1121–Female":"1121–Kuollut","1147–1194":"1147–1194","1149–Male":"1149–Kuollut","1151–Female":"1151–Kuollut","1091–Male":"1091–Kuollut","1091":"1091","1117":"1117","1149":"1149","1215":"1215","1147":"1147","1224":"1224","1121":"1121","1151":"1151","1194":"1194","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1117–":"1117–Décédé","1117–Male":